```json
{
  "projectId": "your-project-id",
  "reporters": "savescreenshots",
  "screenshot": {
    "capture": "automatic"
  },
  "video": false,
  "defaultCommandTimeout": 60000,
  "supportFile": "support/index.js",
  "pluginsFile": "plugins/index.js"
}
```
This configuration enables the SaveScreenshots reporter and sets the default command timeout to 60 seconds.
4. Create a `support/index.js` file in your project's `cypress` directory:
```javascript
// cypress/support/index.js

Cypress.on('uncaught:exception', (err, runnable) => {
  // Fail the test with a custom message and screenshot
  runnable.fail(err.message, {
    screenshot: Cypress.screenshot(),
  });
});
```
This support file listens for uncaught exceptions and fails the test with a custom message and screenshot.
5. Create a `plugins/index.js` file in your project's `cypress` directory:
```javascript
// cypress/plugins/index.js

module.exports = (on, config) => {
  // Add custom logic to the 'before:run' hook
  on('before:run', () => {
    // Your custom logic here
  });

  // Add custom logic to the 'after:run' hook
  on('after:run', () => {
    // Your custom logic here
  });
};
```
This plugins file allows you to add custom logic to the 'before:run' and 'after:run' hooks.
6. Create a `reporters/savescreenshots.js` file in your project's `cypress` directory:
```javascript
// cypress/reporters/savescreenshots.js

class SaveScreenshotsReporter {
  static init() {}

  static afterSuites(results) {
    results.screenshots.forEach((screenshot, index) => {
      const filename = `screenshot-${index}.png`;
      const filepath = path.join(__dirname, '../screenshots', filename);

      fs.writeFileSync(filepath, screenshot.base64, 'base64');
      console.log(`Saved screenshot to ${filepath}`);
    });
  }
}

module.exports = SaveScreenshotsReporter;
```
This reporter class saves the screenshots taken during test execution to the `screenshots` directory.
7. Build the Docker image:
	* Navigate to your project root in the terminal
	* Run: `docker build -t cypress-testing-framework .`
8. Run the tests with Docker:
	* Run: `docker run -d --name cypress-testing-framework cypress-testing-framework`
	* The tests will run in a Docker container, and screenshots will be saved to the host machine's `screenshots` directory

This framework provides a robust and customizable setup for running Cypress tests with Docker, and it captures screenshots during test execution. You can further customize the `before:run` and `after:run` hooks in the `plugins/index.js` file to add your own logic.

Here's a C++ function that takes a reference to a `std::string` containing Markdown formatted text and returns a `std::string` containing HTML formatted text. This function uses the CommonMark specification for Markdown parsing (<https://commonmark.org/>):
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <vector>
#include <sstream>

// CommonMark-compliant Markdown parser (<https://github.com/jgm/cmark>)
#include <cmark/cmark.h>
#include <cmark/cmark_html.h>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    // Initialize the Markdown parser
    cmark_parser *parser = cmark_parser_new(CMARK_PARSER_DEFAULT);
    cmark_node *root = cmark_parser_parse(parser, markdown.c_str());

    // Initialize the HTML renderer
    cmark_html_renderer *renderer = cmark_html_renderer_new(CMARK_HTML_RENDERER_DEFAULT);

    // Generate the HTML string
    std::stringstream html;
    cmark_html_renderer_render(renderer, root, html.rdbuf());

    // Clean up and return the HTML string
    cmark_node_free(root);
    cmark_html_renderer_free(renderer);
    cmark_parser_free(parser);

    return html.str();
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "# Hello, World!\n\nThis is a test of the Markdown to HTML converter.\n\n* Item 1\n* Item 2\n* Item 3";

    std::string html = markdownToHtml(markdown);

    std::cout << html << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```
This code uses the `cmark` library to parse and render the Markdown text. The `markdownToHtml` function takes a `std::string` containing Markdown text and returns a `std::string` containing the corresponding HTML text. The `main` function demonstrates how to use the `markdownToHtml` function to convert a sample Markdown string to HTML.

Please note that you will need to install the `cmark` library to use this code. You can find the installation instructions and more information about the library in the official repository: <https://github.com/jgm/cmark>

